liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Food, medicines, water purifiers, hygiene products and blankets: the aid has been piling up in Egypt's Sinai region at El Arish airport, which even opened an extra landing strip to cope with deliveries. Rafah, the border crossing into Gaza that Egypt had promised to open on Friday, is a few dozen kilometres to the east. It is the only crossing into the blockaded Palestinian territory that is not controlled by Israel. Ahmed Ali, head of the Egyptian Red Crescent, told AFP his organisation receives "two to three planes of aid a day, chartered by humanitarian agencies or states", who want to send food, water or medical supplies to the 2.4 million Palestinians in Gaza. As soon as aid is dropped off on the tarmac, the shipments are loaded onto trucks. Egyptian state-linked broadcaster Al Qahera News said the Rafa crossing would open on Friday. But later Egypt said it needed more time, to repair the roads that connect its territory to Gaza after four Israeli bombings of the crossing. In the meantime, pallets loaded with aid are stored in warehouses in El Arish, the capital of North Sinai, said Ali. As soon as the green light is given, 250 volunteers are ready to transport them to the border. The deal struck by US President Joe Biden with Israel and Egypt will allow in 20 trucks. The emergencies director of the World Health Organization has called it "a drop in the ocean of need". "It should be 2,000 trucks," Michael Ryan said. AFP
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: 'It should be 2,000 trucks': At the gates of Gaza, aid piles up in Egypt

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The former PwC Australia partner at the heart of the controversial tax leaks scandal has been banned from providing financial services for eight years. The Australian Securities and Investments Commission (ASIC) on Friday said Peter Collins was "not a fit and proper person to provide financial services" and that it was in the public interest for him to be barred from working in the sector for a period. ASIC found that Mr Collins disclosed confidential information he obtained in his roles as a tax advisor to the Commonwealth Treasury and the Australian Board of Taxation. For the duration of his ban, Mr Collins cannot provide financial services, control an entity that carries on a financial services business or perform any function involved in the carrying on of a financial services business. Mr Collins has the right to apply to the Administrative Appeals Tribunal for a review of ASIC's decision. Watch my previous story about the PwC tax leaks sandal here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7y1EPFS1MdY And more from my colleague David Chau here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EqEYavUTFek

ASIC found that Mr Collins disclosed confidential information he obtained in his roles as a tax advisor to the Commonwealth Treasury and the Australian Board of Taxation.

For the duration of his ban, Mr Collins cannot provide financial services, control an entity that carries on a financial services business or perform any function involved in the carrying on of a financial services business.
Mr Collins has the right to apply to the Administrative Appeals Tribunal for a review of ASIC's decision.

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: AMP's chief economist Shane Oliver says the next 12 months are likely to see "a further easing in inflation pressure and central banks moving to get off the brakes", but that "the risk of a further leg down in global and Australian shares remains high". "The new highs in bond yields are putting increasing pressure on share market valuations which are already stretched," Dr Oliver said on Friday in a research note. "Central banks are continuing to signal high for longer interest rates; the risk of recession remains high; the risk of an escalation to involve Iran in the Israeli conflict which would directly threaten oil supplies is high." He warns this would add to inflation and recession fears. Dr Oliver also notes that uncertainty remains high around China's economy and property markets and the US remains at high risk of a shutdown next month. "So, the ride for shares is likely to remain volatile," he said. The Australian dollar was also "at risk of more downside in the short term". This was because of "a less hawkish RBA and global uncertainties". "But a rising trend is likely over the next 12 months, reflecting a downtrend in the overvalued US dollar and the Fed moving to cut rates," he said. Read more ABC News coverage about the impact the Middle East conflict is having. Here's analysis that I did about the impact of the conflict on oil and the global economy last week: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2023-10-13/israel-war-against-hamas-iran-oil-price-economy-global-recession/102968608 And here's Ian Verrender's analysis about the impact on markets from earlier this week: https://www.abc.net.au/news/2023-10-17/why-global-financial-markets-are-walking-a-tightrope/102983986
